{{Infobox stadium | name = Anteater Stadium | nickname = | image = | fullname = Anteater Stadium | former_names = | location = 4000 Mesa Rd., [[Irvine, California|Irvine]], California 92617 | coordinates = {{coord|33|39|0|N|117|51|3|W|display=it|type:landmark}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = | renovated =2000 | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[University of California, Irvine]] | operator = | surface = [[Bermuda grass]] | scoreboard = | construction_cost = | suites = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = 2,500 | record_attendance = 1,832 (15 November 2008, Big West Conference men's soccer tournament final) | dimensions = | tenants = {{Plainlist| *[[UC Irvine Anteaters]] men's soccer *UC Irvine Anteaters women's soccer *UC Irvine Anteaters men's track and field *UC Irvine Anteaters women's track and field *[[Orange County Blues FC]] <small>(2013–2016)</small> *[[USC Trojans football]] <small>(practice venue, c. 2000)</small> }} }}
'''Anteater Stadium''' is a 2,500-seat<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ucirvinesports.com/inside_uci/facilities/anteaterstadium/index|title=Anteater Stadium|last=|first=|date=|website=UCIrvineSports.com|publisher=UC Irvine Athletics|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref> [[multi-purpose stadium]] with a [[bermuda grass]] field<ref name=":1" /> on the campus of [[University of California, Irvine]] in [[Irvine, California|Irvine]], California, United States. It is used by the [[UC Irvine Anteaters]] men's & women's soccer and track and field teams.<ref name=":1" />
==History== The stadium hosted the women's division of the [[1973 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]]. The [[USC Trojans football]] team used the stadium for practices around 2000.<ref name=":0" /> In 2000, renovations added lights to Anteater Stadium.<ref name=":0">{{cite news |title=Irvine's Anteater Stadium Getting Ready for Bright New Look |date=26 September 2000 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/sep/26/sports/sp-27042 |accessdate=7 October 2009 | first=Paul | last=McLeod| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091024082411/http://articles.latimes.com/2000/sep/26/sports/sp-27042| archivedate= 24 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Anteater Stadium hosted the 2008 [[Big West Conference]] men's soccer tournament. The tournament final was the most-attended event at the stadium, with 1,832 people present.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=No. 8 Anteaters Beat No. 19 UC Santa Barbara 4-2; Win Big West Tournament|date=15 November 2008|publisher=UC Irvine Athletics|location=Irvine, California|url=http://www.ucirvinesports.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/111608aaa.html|access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref> The stadium was the home stadium for [[United Soccer League]] minor-league professional soccer team [[Orange County Blues]] (now Orange County SC) from 2013 to 2016.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}
