{{coord|37.2735|-76.7152|type:landmark_region:US-VA|display=title}} {{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Jimmye Laycock Football Center | nickname = | image = [[Image:Jimmye Laycock Football Center.jpg|250px]]| location = [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg, VA]]| broke_ground = 2006 | opened = June 21, 2008 | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[College of William & Mary]] | operator = | surface = | construction_cost = $11,000,000| architect = Moseley Architects| former_names = | tenants = [[William & Mary Tribe football]] (2008-present) | seating_capacity = | }} The '''Jimmye Laycock Football Center''' ('''JLFC''') is a [[American football|football]] facility for [[The College of William & Mary]] [[William & Mary Tribe football|Tribe]] in [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]], USA.<ref>[http://www.tribeathletics.com/story.php/7128/ Tribe Athletics - William and Mary to Host Public Open House of Laycock Complex]. Retrieved on June 30, 2008.</ref> The $11 million, {{convert|30000|sqft|m2|sing=on}} building was constructed right next to [[Zable Stadium]] where the Tribe play all home games.<ref name=NEW>[http://www.tribeathletics.com/story.php/4790/ Tribe Athletics - The Jimmye Laycock Football Center]. Retrieved on June 30, 2008.</ref> The facility is named after William & Mary's current, and most successful, football coach [[Jimmye Laycock]], and the cost of the project was funded entirely through private donations.
The JLFC was dedicated on June 21, 2008, and among those in attendance were former William & Mary [[wide receiver]] and present [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] head coach [[Mike Tomlin]] (Class of 1994), former [[Buffalo Bills]] head coach [[Marv Levy]], current [[Virginia Tech Hokies football]] head coach [[Frank Beamer]], and former William & Mary athletic director (1981-85) [[Jim Copeland]].<ref>[http://www.tribeathletics.com/story.php/7051/ Tribe Athletics – W&M to Dedicate Jimmye Laycock Football Center on June 21]. Retrieved on June 30, 2008.</ref>
