{{refimprove|date=March 2015}} {{infobox baseball team | name = Nagoya Kinko | established = 1936 | color1 = | color2 = | logo = | cap_logo = | league = [[Japanese Baseball League]] | former_leagues = | uniform = | retirednumbers = | colors = | nicknames = | former_names = Nagoya Golden Dolphins (1936) | ballpark = | pastparks = | series = | series_champs = | division_champ_type = | division_champs = | owner = [[Nagoya Shimbun]] | manager = Genzaburo Okada (1936–1940)<ref name=BR /> | gm = | current = }} '''Nagoya Kinko''' (long name: '''Nagoya Kinnosachihiko''')<ref name=BR>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Nagoya_Kinko "Nagoya Kinko"], Baseball-Reference.com. Accessed Mar. 8, 2015.</ref> was a [[Japanese baseball]] team that played in the [[Japanese Baseball League]] (JBL) before it merged with another team. It was owned by the daily broadsheet ''[[Nagoya Shimbun]]''.<ref name=BR />
The club was founded as the '''Nagoya Golden Dolphins''' before the 1936 JBL season. In 1937 the team changed its name to Nagoya Kinko.
The franchise never had a winning record and never placed higher than fourth in the league standings. Few players wanted to play for the team,<ref name=BR /> and it merged with the [[Tsubasa Baseball Club]] after the 1940 season to form the '''[[Taiyō Baseball Club]]'''; that franchise was dissolved following the 1944 JBL season.
